THE SAPS police management in Mpumalanga calls to an end to the barbaric attack on police officials. This comes after the recent incidents of police attacks. Brigadier Selvy Mohlala told Daily Sun that two Witbank Flying Squad members who were on routine patrol offered to render an assistance to a motorist who had a breakdown. Whilst still busy rendering assistance, another motorist stopped on an opposite direction close to the members. "Members had to attend to a second vehicle to investigate. To their suprise, when approaching the second vehicle, they noticed that the road was barricaded with rocks," said Mohlala. The members then decided to remove the rocks to ensure the safety of other motorists. You must be SIGNED IN to read comments "From the dense dark bushes in the night, it is alleged that about seven fully armed suspects came from the dense bushes and fired several shots directed to the members" said Mohlala. "Members had no option but to return fire," he added. He further explained that during that unnecessary attack, one of the members was shot in the abdomen. "The other member managed to rescue his colleague from the scene and quickly rushed him to hospital for medical attention where he is currently recovering," he said. The Provincial Commissioner of the SAPS in Mpumalanga, Lieutenant General Semakaleng Daphney condemned the unnecessary attack on police officials. "Criminals must have an understanding that members of the police's responsibility is to protect and safeguard all the inhibitance of the Republic and not to act against the community" the General warned. 